   186	## §5. Recommendations for incubation-checkpoint
   187	
   188	- Re-read the goal articulation and explicitly choose the context mix before choosing the R mix. My synthesis read is Context A primary with Context F/B adjacency, but that is interpretive and Logan's read is binding.
   189	- Do not ask "R2 or not?" as a binary. Ask which of the four extension/configuration/orchestration surfaces can carry the first concrete target, and only then whether R1/R3/R5 are needed.
   190	- Treat R4 as first-class in the checkpoint. The evidence base repeatedly shows composable primitives and headless/machine surfaces; forcing these into R2 would be a silent-default narrowing.
   191	- Require source/runtime verification before relying on any default behavior surfaced only in README or user docs. Specific checks: reassessment default, team-mode effective preferences, extension compatibility enforcement, and release workflow state advancement.
   192	- If proceeding, pick a first second-wave target that tests the frame cheaply. Good candidates: effective-state visibility; a release metadata/checklist artifact linked to milestones; a Context A/F long-arc decision trace skill/workflow; or a headless orchestration recipe. Avoid starting with Pi seam refactoring or deterministic release engines unless incubation explicitly decides those are load-bearing.
   193	- If R5 becomes live, dispatch a competitor/sibling-harness landscape probe before design. The current evidence says gsd-2 is useful and instructive, not that it must be the sole substrate.
