   349	### §5.5 Cross-axis integration — how the four axes compose at incubation
   350	
   351	- **Composition observation.** The four axes (§5.1 metaquestion / §5.2 R-mix / §5.3 context-anchoring / §5.4 side-probes) are not independent. Per the comparison's reading:
   352	  - Context-anchoring (§5.3) is the most upstream axis: shapes whether §1.4 release machinery + §1.9 R3 + §1.2 surface-stability are load-bearing for the chosen context-mix.
   353	  - Metaquestion (§5.1) flows from context-anchoring: direction-holds-with-qualifications net read holds across most context-anchorings; qualification-load varies by context.
   354	  - R-mix (§5.2) flows from context-anchoring + first-target-shape: which R2 subsystem + whether R3/R5 become live depends on context + first-target.
   355	  - Side-probes (§5.4) flow from first-target-shape + R-mix: which probes fire pre-vs-post depends on what the second-wave-scoping commits to.
   356	- **Implication for incubation deliberation order.** Per both syntheses' §5 recommendations + this comparison's read, an efficient incubation ordering is: **(1) dispose context-anchoring (§5.3); (2) test metaquestion-direction-holds under that anchoring (§5.1); (3) select first-target-shape candidate (§5.2 question (b)); (4) decide R-mix decomposition for that target (§5.2 question (a) — §2.1 disposition-timing); (5) fire pre-required side-probes (§5.4).** This is a comparison-author surface, not a disposition; Logan disposes incubation deliberation order.
   357	- **Comparison-author caveat.** Per `framing-widening §3.3`: incubation is Logan-led + out of orchestration scope. The comparison surfaces axis-composition; it does not pre-decide incubation deliberation order or the dispositions at each axis.
